<font color="#FF0000">PTSD THE GREAT HEALER</font><br>
<tt>Mon Sep 22 19:07:42 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
<br>
PTSD the great healer<br><br>
Ed and others, this is me, Cook, yes its long but I hope what I say makes sense. Its what I have dealt with and it may not make any sense at all to the rest of you. I hope it does. It just maybe that I am moving into an area we don't want to visit or even consider. I share it here because I don't know any better.<br><br>
Suppose we stopped the PTSD merry-go-round. No more treatment no more shrinks no more voodoo medications, no more pain and sorrow. What would happen if we took control as Ed has suggested? <br><br>
I don't believe I suffer from PTSD, perhaps I did or do, I don't know. Perhaps I have dealt with it somehow, and somewhere and somehow broke free from its grip, and learned how to control it.<br>
We have looked at the symptoms, as varied as they are. We have looked at treatment as varied as they are and we have looked at the cause as varied as they are. But what if we just dealt with it allowed it to surface in order to deal with those demons in our lives.<br><br>
The question is, why does our mind, body, spirit react to PTSD? <br>
Something happened, some tragic event in our past that we either dealt with or now have to deal with because it keeps overshadowing our lives. <br>
Human history shows us that human beings have had to deal with major tragedies throughout life. Some of those events have come from natural forces, tidal waves, earthquakes, hurricanes, fires etc. Others have been thrown upon us by our own devices; the nuclear bomb dropped on Hiroshima. One moment your family's there the next moment they're gone. War has produced a number of causalities throughout the ages, and I believe PTSD is not all just related to Vietnam but to the circumstances that surrounded our action and rejection by others for being there. Because of this the conquering hero was not welcomed back with open arms. Because of this we were not allowed to deal with, share or speak with others about what we witnessed, saw or confronted in the jungles of Vietnam. <br><br>
Since a national day of healing for Vietnam vets is not on the government's agenda at this time. Through I believe a National day of honor to those who served would heal a lot of wounds for the Vietnam veteran, we find ourselves once again having to deal with this ourselves. What can we do?<br><br>
Why do we need to suffer from PTSD? Why not use it as a healing tool? Somehow, somewhere something happened and we needed to deal with it but didn't or we dealt with it by placing it in the back of our minds but our minds have had no rest since that time and its tired and wants some rest. <br><br>
Does PTSD then surface so that we can deal with it? Is it part of our human nature that keeps surfacing and we keep pushing it down. Perhaps it surfaces so that the healing process may begin?<br>
What if PTSD is essentially an inner healing process, a natural response to specific circumstances that we have never dealt within our lives? It maybe just a natural need to set to rest what we never confronted.<br><br>
The problem I see is that we are not properly equipped to deal with it, or for that matter do not know how to cooperate with it. So when PTSD surfaces among those of us who are ripe for healing we dismiss it or shove it back down for fear of losing what control we do have. <br>
Because of this the vet whose mind and body is ready for healing, experiences PTSD more often then the individual that is not ready or the vet who has come to gripes with its cause, effects and who has learned how to deal with it by gaining control.<br><br>
Letting it run its course may very well be what our minds are telling us that it wants to do, without drugs or half witted shrinks infesting and polluting what images and trauma they cannot possibly understand.  To them they see only scrambled eggs. We knew the size and shape of the product before it fell apart.<br><br>
There are a lot of questions going through my mind and I need to stop, but let's say. There must be a natural reason why PTSD surfaces. <br>
What if we (in control) allow only a small part of the PTSD conflict within us to surface if even for only a very small time?<br>
Let me share with you from a personal experience. As a Marine I learned that I must be in control, for my sake and the sake of the Marine next to me. He depended upon me to be there for him. <br>
As a police officer I had to be always in control and be willing to make split second decisions that could have tremendous consequences. Military and war veterans make some of the best police officers in our land because they have had to deal with explosive situations and learned to control themselves in those situations. When you're home that control however must be set aside, you cannot transfer or use it in attempts to control your family life, otherwise you'll be running a boot camp at home or having everyone lined up against the wall every evening. Your job is one thing your home life another. Nam was a foreign land, and unfortunately or perhaps fortunately some of us were in combat one day and in Hollywood the next. Two different worlds and we found that the same military service that took us to the land of no postage stamps brought us back without so much as a kiss on the cheek to thank us for having served.<br>
The thing is, we had no control over this. <br>
Why is Ed so interested in discussing control? Because we all are. Why is control so important to us?<br>
Because we experienced something traumatic over which we had no control. Because of this and other associated factors we felt helpless and experienced hopelessness and PTSD attached itself to us like the space alien in the movie ALIEN. However we keep renting the video and watching Alien I, II, &amp; III over and over again and wonder why were so messed up.<br>
I look at PTSD like that alien invader that must be dealt with, it doesn't belong in our lives and it is not part of our lives. It is part of our past but we must know how it will be part of our future, if it must be there at all. Since we were in a position at that time of venerability and helplessness at the time it invaded our body, mind and spirit, we sort of shut down our body in order to protect ourselves from this foreign invader. We shut ourselves down instead of dealing with it then and there because we were not prepared to deal with it at that time. But in the process we became victims of the aliens embrace, we found ourselves helpless because we could not find ways of regaining that control we once had. We found ourselves locked in, like the Korean War and Israel's wars, no workable solutions can be found. Our body therefore finally gave up and in this weaken state the alien arose. <br><br>
That scared us so we gained control of it as soon as we could through help any type of help. Drugs, shrinks, alcohol, women, you name it anything and everything that would help us get our minds off the demons from hell. Some of us took it out on our love ones and anything and everything that would dare to get in our face. We found ourselves feeling worthless and abandoned, except by those who understand and who shared with us the same fear and woes. <br>
Here's where control comes in. In order for our self-esteem to survive and for us to have a sense of competence we must feel we are in control of our lives. Without that control, helplessness and hopelessness sets in and this causes the alien to surface once again.<br>
We hate this because after all we are men; we served in the Marine Corps, in the_______(fill in the blank). The problem is we find that we are not equipped to psychologically deal with it. So what do we do?<br>
What did I do?<br>
I don't know if this would help, but in order to gain control I had to relinquish what control I did have.  I did this in Nam; I Cried havoc let loose the dogs of war and asked the creator to take care of me. Went into the thick of battle and used the terror of the night instead of allowing it to absorb me. <br>
When I found I had survived I thanked God and went on. But, somehow I knew that I had truly placed my trust in him and because of that I could move on. <br>
After that, unknowingly I began to give him control over my life, little by little and soon God and I dealt with the demons of my life. t was not pretty, cried unto him and finally felt Cleansed. I had to come to the realization that there was a bigger Marine that I and I submitted to him. Found out that he was the ultimate controller, so I had nothing to loose.  <br>
The product was I stopped drinking 20 years ago. I was then able to give love without fear of rejection, because I gave it free without wanting any back in return. I experienced joy because it was not based on happiness but true joy from within. Maybe I did have PTSD, and maybe I just shot it full of holes, until it could not come after me, because it no longer had any substance or meaning and now, now I sleep at night.<br>
In peace and war<br>
Cook<br>

